CC  This model describes recently identified adenosine 5'-phosphosulfate (APS) reductase activity found in sulfate-assimilatory prokaryotes, thus separating it from the traditionally described phosphoadenosine 5'-phosphosulfate (PAPS) reductases found in bacteria and fungi [1]. Homologous to PAPS reductase in enterobacteria, cyanobacteria, and yeast, APS reductase here clusters with, and demonstrates greater homology to plant APS reductase. Additionally, the presence of two conserved C-terminal motifs (CCXXRKXXPL & SXGCXXCT) distinguishes APS substrate specificity and serves as a FeS cluster [2].
